earn_20260429_075816.log\n60\t\n61\t---\n62\t## Session 2 -- 2026-04-29 07:58\n63\t\n64\tAdded two generalization strategies in `agent/active_operators.py`:\n65\t\n66\t- **`rect_interior_fill`** -- detects hollow rectangular borders of a single\n67\t  foreground color on a background, learns a map\n68\t  `(interior_h, interior_w) -> fill_color` from training pairs, and fills\n69\t  matching rectangle interiors in the test input. Solves c0f76784.\n70\t- **`staircase_extend_right`** -- detects 1-row inputs that produce\n71\t  triangular outputs of `w//2` rows where each row's colored prefix grows\n72\t  by one cell. Identifies fg as the leftmost cell and bg as the only\n73\t  other color (avoids a \"most common color = bg\" trap when fg fills most\n74\t  of the row). Solves bbc9ae5d.\n75\t\n76\tVerification:\n77\t- `python run_task.py` (regression on 08ed6ac7): CORRECT\n78\t- `python run_learn.py --limit 20 --shuffle`: 4 / 20 (20.0%), up from 2 / 20\n79\t  - c0f76784: CORRECT via rect_interior_fill (pipeline)\n80\t  - bbc9ae5d: CORRECT via staircase_extend_right (pipeline)\n81\t  - 8be77c9e, c59eb873: CORRECT via stored rules\n82\t- Rules: 5 -> 7 (+2 new strategies stored in procedural_memory/)\n83\t\n84\t---\n85\t## Learning Loop -- 2026-04-29 07:59\n86\t\n87\t- Split: None, Tasks: 20\n88\t- Correct: 4 / 20 (20.0%)\n89\t- Rules: 7 -> 7 (+0 learned)\n90\t- Stored rule hits: 4\n91\t- Time: 8s\n92\t- Log: logs/learn_20260429_075851.log\n93\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"3fed7f85-792d-4d37-88c2-f10a44b2632b","uuid":"1500db1c-06b4-4579-bfc7-8efe6d62d9df","timestamp":"2026-04-28T22:59:05.961Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/Users/sir_k/Desktop/SOAR-ARC-test/logs/session_log.md","content":"\n---\n## Learning Loop -- 2026-04-29 07:50\n\n- Split: None, Tasks: 20\n- Correct: 0 / 20 (0.0%)\n- Rules: 0 -> 3 (+3 learned)\n- Stored rule hits: 0\n- Time: 13s\n- Log: logs/learn_20260429_075023.log\n\n---\n## Learning Loop -- 2026-04-29 07:52\n\n- Split: None, Tasks: 20\n- Correct: 2 / 20 (10.0%)\n- Rules: 3 -> 5 (+2 learned)\n- Stored rule hits: 0\n- Time: 9s\n- Log: logs/learn_20260429_075239.log\n\n---\n## Session 1 -- 2026-04-29 07:52\n\nAdded two generalization strategies in `agent/active_operators.py`:\n\n- **`integer_upscale`** -- detects when output dimensions are k * input\n  dimensions (same k for height and width across all examples) and each\n  input cell becomes a kxk block of the same color. Solves c59eb873.\n- **`stack_with_mirror`** -- detects when output is the input concatenated\n  with a flipped copy of itself along an axis. Tries vertical/horizontal x\n  input-first/flip-first (4 configurations). Solves 8be77c9e.\n\nVerification:\n- `python run_task.py` (regression on 08ed6ac7): CORRECT\n- `python run_learn.py --limit 20 --shuffle`: 2 / 20 (10.0%), up from 0 / 20\n  - 8be77c9e: CORRECT via stack_with_mirror\n  - c59eb873: CORRECT via integer_upscale\n- Rules: 3 -> 5 (+2 new strategies stored in procedural_memory/)\n\n---\n## Learning Loop -- 2026-04-29 07:53\n\n- Split: None, Tasks: 20\n- Correct: 2 / 20 (10.0%)\n- Rules: 5 -> 5 (+0 learned)\n- Stored rule hits: 2\n- Time: 9s\n- Log: logs/learn_20260429_075320.log\n\n---\n## Learning Loop -- 2026-04-29 07:58\n\n- Split: None, Tasks: 20\n- Correct: 4 / 20 (20.0%)\n- Rules: 5 -> 7 (+2 learned)\n- Stored rule hits: 2\n- Time: 8s\n- Log: logs/learn_20260429_075816.log\n\n---\n## Session 2 -- 2026-04-29 07:58\n\nAdded two generalization strategies in `agent/active_operators.py`:\n\n- **`rect_interior_fill`** -- detects hollow rectangular borders of a single\n  foreground color on a background, learns a map\n  `(interior_h, interior_w) -> fill_color` from training pairs, and fills\n  matching rectangle interiors in the test input. Solves c0f76784.\n- **`staircase_extend_right`** -- detects 1-row inputs that produce\n  triangular outputs of `w//2` rows where each row's colored prefix grows\n  by one cell. Identifies fg as the leftmost cell and bg as the only\n  other color (avoids a \"most common color = bg\" trap when fg fills most\n  of the row). Solves bbc9ae5d.\n\nVerification:\n- `python run_task.py` (regression on 08ed6ac7): CORRECT\n- `python run_learn.py --limit 20 --shuffle`: 4 / 20 (20.0%), up from 2 / 20\n  - c0f76784: CORRECT via rect_interior_fill (pipeline)\n  - bbc9ae5d: CORRECT via staircase_extend_right (pipeline)\n  - 8be77c9e, c59eb873: CORRECT via stored rules\n- Rules: 5 -> 7 (+2 new strategies stored in procedural_memory/)\n\n---\n## Learning Loop -- 2026-04-29 07:59\n\n- Split: None, Tasks: 20\n- Correct: 4 / 20 (20.0%)\n- Rules: 7 -> 7 (+0 learned)\n- Stored rule hits: 4\n- Time: 8s\n- Log: logs/learn_20260429_075851.log\n","numLines":93,"startLine":1,"totalLines":93}}}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01EMnWLaFzrJNxRU3q8jUwkP","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t\"\"\"\n2\tactive_operators -- SOAR Operator implementations.\n3\t\n4\tPipeline operators (all fire in S2, read/write S1):\n5\t  SelectTargetOperator  -> set up comparison agenda from example pairs\n6\t  CompareOperator       -> execute one comparison using ARCKG compare()\n7\t  ExtractPatternOperator-> cell-level analysis of input/output changes\n8\t  GeneralizeOperator    -> create transformation rule from patterns\n9\t  PredictOperator       -> apply rule to test input\n10\t  SubmitOperator        -> write prediction to output-link, satisfy goal\n11\t\"\"\"\n12\t\n13\tfrom agent.operators import Operator\n14\tfrom ARCKG.comparison import compare as arckg_compare\n15\t\n16\t\n17\t# ======================================================================\n18\t# SolveTaskOperator -- abstract top-level goal (S1)\n19\t# ======================================================================\n20\t\n21\tclass SolveTaskOperator(Operator):\n22\t    \"\"\"\n23\t    Abstract operator at S1. Intentionally makes no WM change so\n24\t    the cycle detects no-change and creates an S2 substate.\n25\t    \"\"\"\n26\t\n27\t    def __init__(self):\n28\t        super().__init__(\"solve-task\")\n29\t        self.proposal_preference = \"+\"\n30\t\n31\t    def precondition(self, wm) -> bool:\n32\t        raise NotImplementedError(\"SolveTaskOperator.precondition() not implemented.\")\n33\t\n34\t    def effect(self, wm):\n35\t        # Intentionally empty -- triggers no-change impasse -> S2\n36\t        return\n37\t\n38\t\n39\t# ======================================================================\n40\t# SelectTargetOperator -- set up comparison agenda\n41\t# ======================================================================\n42\t\n43\tclass SelectTargetOperator(Operator):\n44\t    \"\"\"\n45\t    Reads wm.task to find example pairs and sets up comparison targets.\n46\t    For each example pair: compare input grid (G0) vs output grid (G1).\n47\t    Writes comparison-agenda, pending-comparisons, and empty comparisons to S1.\n48\t    \"\"\"\n49\t\n50\t    def __init__(self):\n51\t        super().__init__(\"select_target\")\n52\t\n53\t    def precondition(self, wm) -> bool:\n54\t        raise NotImplementedError(\"SelectTargetOperator.precondition() not implemented.\")\n55\t\n56\t    def effect(self, wm):\n57\t        task = wm.task\n58\t        if task is None:\n59\t            return\n60\t\n61\t        agenda = []\n62\t        pending = []\n63\t\n64\t        for idx, pair in enumerate(task.example_pairs):\n65\t            if pair.input_grid is not None and pair.output_grid is not None:\n66\t                spec = {\n67\t                    \"type\": \"grid\",\n68\t                    \"pair_idx\": idx,\n69\t                    \"pair_type\": \"example\",\n70\t                    \"id1\": pair.input_grid.node_id,\n71\t                    \"id2\": pair.output_grid.node_id,\n72\t                }\n73\t                agenda.append(spec)\n74\t                pending.append(spec)\n75\t\n76\t        # Build node lookup so CompareOperator can find ARCKG nodes by ID\n77\t        node_lookup = {}\n78\t        for pair in task.example_pairs + task.test_pairs:\n79\t            if pair.input_grid:\n80\t                node_lookup[pair.input_grid.node_id] = pair.input_grid\n81\t            if pair.output_grid:\n82\t                node_lookup[pair.output_grid.node_id] = pair.output_grid\n83\t        wm.node_lookup = node_lookup\n84\t\n85\t        wm.s1[\"comparison-agenda\"] = agenda\n86\t        wm.s1[\"pending-comparisons\"] = pending\n87\t        wm.s1[\"comparisons\"] = {}\n88\t\n89\t\n90\t# ======================================================================\n91\t# CompareOperator -- execute one comparison\n92\t# ======================================================================\n93\t\n94\tclass CompareOperator(Operator):\n95\t    \"\"\"\n96\t    Pops one item from pending-comparisons, calls ARCKG compare(),\n97\t    and stores the result in the comparisons dict on S1.\n98\t    \"\"\"\n99\t\n100\t    def __init__(self, compare_fn=None):\n101\t        super().__init__(\"compare\")\n102\t        self._compare_fn = compare_fn\n103\t\n104\t    def precondition(self, wm) -> bool:\n105\t        raise NotImplementedError(\"CompareOperator.precondition() not implemented.\")\n106\t\n107\t    def effect(self, wm):\n108\t        pending = list(wm.s1.get(\"pending-comparisons\") or [])\n109\t        if not pending:\n110\t            return\n111\t\n112\t        item = pending.pop(0)\n113\t\n114\t        # Find the actual ARCKG nodes\n115\t        node_lookup = getattr(wm, \"node_lookup\", {})\n116\t        node_a = node_lookup.get(item[\"id1\"])\n117\t        node_b = node_lookup.get(item[\"id2\"])\n118\t\n119\t        if node_a is None or node_b is None:\n120\t            wm.s1[\"pending-comparisons\"] = pending\n121\t            return\n122\t\n123\t        # Execute comparison\n124\t        fn = self._compare_fn or arckg_compare\n125\t        result = fn(node_a, node_b)\n126\t\n127\t        # Store result keyed by type and pair index\n128\t        key = f\"{item['type']}_{item.get('pair_idx', 0)}\"\n129\t        comparisons = dict(wm.s1.get(\"comparisons\") or {})\n130\t        comparisons[key] = {\"spec\": item, \"result\": result}\n131\t\n132\t        wm.s1[\"pending-comparisons\"] = pending\n133\t        wm.s1[\"comparisons\"] = comparisons\n134\t\n135\t\n136\t# ======================================================================\n137\t# ExtractPatternOperator -- cell-level transformation analysis\n138\t# ======================================================================\n139\t\n140\tclass ExtractPatternOperator(Operator):\n141\t    \"\"\"\n142\t    Analyzes each example pair at the cell level to discover what changes\n143\t    between input and output grids. Groups changed cells into connected\n144\t    components and records color/position information for generalization.\n145\t    \"\"\"\n146\t\n147\t    def __init__(self):\n148\t        super().__init__(\"extract_pattern\")\n149\t\n150\t    def precondition(self, wm) -> bool:\n151\t        raise NotImplementedError(\"ExtractPatternOperator.precondition() not implemented.\")\n152\t\n153\t    def effect(self, wm):\n154\t        task = wm.task\n155\t        if task is None:\n156\t            return\n157\t\n158\t        patterns = {\n159\t            \"grid_size_preserved\": True,\n160\t            \"pair_analyses\": [],\n161\t        }\n162\t\n163\t        for pair in task.example_pairs:\n164\t            g0 = pair.input_grid\n165\t            g1 = pair.output_grid\n166\t            if g0 is None or g1 is None:\n167\t                continue\n168\t\n169\t            analysis = self._analyze_pair(g0, g1)\n170\t            patterns[\"pair_analyses\"].append(analysis)\n171\t\n172\t            if g0.height != g1.height or g0.width != g1.width:\n173\t                patterns[\"grid_size_preserved\"] = False\n174\t\n175\t        wm.s1[\"patterns\"] = patterns\n176\t\n177\t    # ---- internal helpers ------------------------------------------------\n178\t\n179\t    def _analyze_pair(self, g0, g1):\n180\t        \"\"\"Cell-level diff between input and output grid.\"\"\"\n181\t        raw_in = g0.raw\n182\t        raw_out = g1.raw\n183\t        h = min(len(raw_in), len(raw_out))\n184\t        w = min(\n185\t            len(raw_in[0]) if raw_in else 0,\n186\t            len(raw_out[0]) if raw_out else 0,\n187\t        )\n188\t\n189\t        changes = []\n190\t        for r in range(h):\n191\t            for c in range(w):\n192\t                if raw_in[r][c] != raw_out[r][c]:\n193\t                    changes.append({\n194\t                        \"row\": r, \"col\": c,\n195\t                        \"input_color\": raw_in[r][c],\n196\t                        \"output_color\": raw_out[r][c],\n197\t                    })\n198\t\n199\t        groups = self._group_changes(changes)\n200\t\n201\t        group_analyses = []\n202\t        for group_cells in groups:\n203\t            input_colors = set()\n204\t            output_colors = set()\n205\t            positions = []\n206\t            for cell in group_cells:\n207\t                input_colors.add(cell[\"input_color\"])\n208\t                output_colors.add(cell[\"output_color\"])\n209\t                positions.append((cell[\"row\"], cell[\"col\"]))\n210\t\n211\t            top_row = min(r for r, c in positions)\n212\t            top_col = min(c for r, c in positions)\n213\t\n214\t            group_analyses.append({\n215\t                \"input_colors\": sorted(input_colors),\n216\t                \"output_colors\": sorted(output_colors),\n217\t                \"top_row\": top_row,\n218\t                \"top_col\": top_col,\n219\t                \"cell_count\": len(group_cells),\n220\t            })\n221\t\n222\t        return {\n223\t            \"total_changes\": len(changes),\n224\t            \"num_groups\": len(groups),\n225\t            \"groups\": group_analyses,\n226\t            \"size_match\": (\n227\t                len(raw_in) == len(raw_out)\n228\t                and (len(raw_in[0]) if raw_in else 0)\n229\t                    == (len(raw_out[0]) if raw_out else 0)\n230\t            ),\n231\t        }\n232\t\n233\t    @staticmethod\n234\t    def _group_changes(changes):\n235\t        \"\"\"Group changed cells into 4-connected components.\"\"\"\n236\t        if not changes:\n237\t            return []\n238\t\n239\t        pos_to_change = {}\n240\t        for c in changes:\n241\t            pos_to_change[(c[\"row\"], c[\"col\"])] = c\n242\t\n243\t        visited = set()\n244\t        groups = []\n245\t\n246\t        for change in changes:\n247\t            pos = (change[\"row\"], change[\"col\"])\n248\t            if pos in visited:\n249\t                continue\n250\t\n251\t            group = []\n252\t            queue = [pos]\n253\t            while queue:\n254\t                p = queue.pop(0)\n255\t                if p in visited or p not in pos_to_change:\n256\t                    continue\n257\t                visited.add(p)\n258\t                group.append(pos_to_change[p])\n259\t                for dr, dc in [(-1, 0), (1, 0), (0, -1), (0, 1)]:\n260\t                    nb = (p[0] + dr, p[1] + dc)\n261\t                    if nb in pos_to_change and nb not in visited:\n262\t                        queue.append(nb)\n263\t            groups.append(group)\n264\t\n265\t        return groups\n266\t\n267\t\n268\t# ======================================================================\n269\t# GeneralizeOperator -- rule creation from patterns\n270\t# ======================================================================\n271\t\n272\tclass GeneralizeOperator(Operator):\n273\t    \"\"\"\n274\t    Reads extracted patterns and attempts to create a transformation rule.\n275\t    Tries multiple strategies in priority order. If no strategy succeeds,\n276\t    falls back to an identity rule so the pipeline can still complete.\n277\t    \"\"\"\n278\t\n279\t    def __init__(self, generalize_fn=None, save_fn=None):\n280\t        super().__init__(\"generalize\")\n281\t        self._generalize_fn = generalize_fn\n282\t        self._save_fn = save_fn\n283\t\n284\t    def precondition(self, wm) -> bool:\n285\t        raise NotImplementedError(\"GeneralizeOperator.precondition() not implemented.\")\n286\t\n287\t    def effect(self, wm):\n288\t        patterns = wm.s1.get(\"patterns\")\n289\t        if not patterns:\n290\t            return\n291\t\n292\t        task = wm.task\n293\t        example_pairs = self._collect_example_pairs(task)\n294\t\n295\t        rule = None\n296\t\n297\t        # Strategy 1: sequential recoloring (e.g., color objects 1, 2, 3, ...)\n298\t        rule = self._try_recolor_sequential(patterns)\n299\t\n300\t        # Strategy 2: bounding-box fill — fill bg cells within bbox of fg color\n301\t        if rule is None:\n302\t            rule = self._try_bbox_fill(example_pairs)\n303\t\n304\t        # Strategy 3: horizontal mirror recolor — recolor cells whose\n305\t        #   horizontal-mirror partner has the same color\n306\t        if rule is None:\n307\t            rule = self._try_axis_mirror_recolor(example_pairs)\n308\t\n309\t        # Strategy 4: integer upscale — each input cell becomes a kxk block\n310\t        if rule is None:\n311\t            rule = self._try_integer_upscale(example_pairs)\n312\t\n313\t        # Strategy 5: stack with mirror — output = concat(input, flip(input))\n314\t        if rule is None:\n315\t            rule = self._try_stack_with_mirror(example_pairs)\n316\t\n317\t        # Strategy 6: rectangle interior fill — hollow rect borders get interior\n318\t        #   filled with a color determined by interior dimensions\n319\t        if rule is None:\n320\t            rule = self._try_rect_interior_fill(example_pairs)\n321\t\n322\t        # Strategy 7: staircase extend right — 1-row input becomes a triangular\n323\t        #   stack of rows where each row's prefix grows by one cell\n324\t        if rule is None:\n325\t            rule = self._try_staircase_extend_right(example_pairs)\n326\t\n327\t        # Strategy 8: simple 1:1 color mapping\n328\t        if rule is None:\n329\t            rule = self._try_color_mapping(patterns)\n330\t\n331\t        # Fallback: identity (copy input as output)\n332\t        if rule is None:\n333\t            rule = {\"type\": \"identity\", \"confidence\": 0.0}\n334\t\n335\t        wm.s1[\"active-rules\"] = [rule]\n336\t\n337\t    @staticmethod\n338\t    def _collect_example_pairs(task):\n339\t        \"\"\"Return list of (raw_input, raw_output) tuples for example pairs.\"\"\"\n340\t        if task is None:\n341\t            return []\n342\t        out = []\n343\t        for pair in task.example_pairs:\n344\t            g0, g1 = pair.input_grid, pair.output_grid\n345\t            if g0 is None or g1 is None:\n346\t                continue\n347\t            out.append((g0.raw, g1.raw))\n348\t        return out\n349\t\n350\t    # ---- strategy: sequential recoloring --------------------------------\n351\t\n352\t    def _try_recolor_sequential(self, patterns):\n353\t        \"\"\"\n354\t        Detect pattern: all changed-cell groups have one source color,\n355\t        output colors are sequential (1,2,3,...), ordered by position.\n356\t        \"\"\"\n357\t        pair_analyses = patterns.get(\"pair_analyses\", [])\n358\t        if not pair_analyses or not patterns.get(\"grid_size_preserved\"):\n359\t            return None\n360\t\n361\t        # All pairs must have the same number of change groups\n362\t        group_counts = [a[\"num_groups\"] for a in pair_analyses]\n363\t        if len(set(group_counts)) != 1 or group_counts[0] == 0:\n364\t            return None\n365\t\n366\t        all_source_colors = set()\n367\t\n368\t        for analysis in pair_analyses:\n369\t            for g in analysis[\"groups\"]:\n370\t                if len(g[\"input_colors\"]) != 1 or len(g[\"output_colors\"]) != 1:\n371\t                    return None\n372\t                all_source_colors.add(g[\"input_colors\"][0])\n373\t\n374\t            out_colors = sorted(set(g[\"output_colors\"][0] for g in analysis[\"groups\"]))\n375\t            expected = list(range(min(out_colors), min(out_colors) + len(out_colors)))\n376\t            if out_colors != expected:\n377\t                return None\n378\t\n379\t        # Try sorting by different position keys\n380\t        for sort_key in [\"top_row\", \"top_col\"]:\n381\t            if self._check_sort_key(pair_analyses, sort_key):\n382\t                start_color = min(\n383\t                    g[\"output_colors\"][0]\n384\t                    for g in pair_analyses[0][\"groups\"]\n385\t                )\n386\t                return {\n387\t                    \"type\": \"recolor_sequential\",\n388\t                    \"sort_key\": sort_key,\n389\t                    \"start_color\": start_color,\n390\t                    \"source_colors\": sorted(all_source_colors),\n391\t                    \"confidence\": 1.0,\n392\t                }\n393\t\n394\t        return None\n395\t\n396\t    @staticmethod\n397\t    def _check_sort_key(pair_analyses, sort_key):\n398\t        \"\"\"Verify that sorting groups by sort_key produces sequential output colors.\"\"\"\n399\t        for analysis in pair_analyses:\n400\t            groups = analysis[\"groups\"]\n401\t            sorted_groups = sorted(groups, key=lambda g: g[sort_key])\n402\t            colors = [g[\"output_colors\"][0] for g in sorted_groups]\n403\t            if colors != list(range(colors[0], colors[0] + len(colors))):\n404\t                return False\n405\t        return True\n406\t\n407\t    # ---- strategy: simple color mapping ---------------------------------\n408\t\n409\t    def _try_color_mapping(self, patterns):\n410\t        \"\"\"\n411\t        Detect pattern: each input color consistently maps to one output color.\n412\t        \"\"\"\n413\t        pair_analyses = patterns.get(\"pair_analyses\", [])\n414\t        if not pair_analyses or not patterns.get(\"grid_size_preserved\"):\n415\t            return None\n416\t\n417\t        # Collect all observed color transitions\n418\t        color_map = {}\n419\t        for analysis in pair_analyses:\n420\t            for group in analysis[\"groups\"]:\n421\t                for ic in group[\"input_colors\"]:\n422\t                    for oc in group[\"output_colors\"]:\n423\t                        if ic not in color_map:\n424\t                            color_map[ic] = set()\n425\t                        color_map[ic].add(oc)\n426\t\n427\t        # Each input color must map to exactly one output color\n428\t        simple_map = {}\n429\t        for ic, ocs in color_map.items():\n430\t            if len(ocs) != 1:\n431\t                return None\n432\t            simple_map[ic] = list(ocs)[0]\n433\t\n434\t        if simple_map:\n435\t            return {\n436\t                \"type\": \"color_mapping\",\n437\t                \"mapping\": simple_map,\n438\t                \"confidence\": 0.8,\n439\t            }\n440\t\n441\t        return None\n442\t\n443\t    # ---- strategy: bounding-box fill ------------------------------------\n444\t\n445\t    def _try_bbox_fill(self, example_pairs):\n446\t        \"\"\"\n447\t        Detect: same grid size; output equals input except every background\n448\t        cell within the bounding box of the foreground color has been\n449\t        recolored to a single marker color (a color not present in input).\n450\t        \"\"\"\n451\t        if not example_pairs:\n452\t            return None\n453\t\n454\t        marker = None\n455\t        bg_color = None\n456\t        fg_color = None\n457\t\n458\t        for raw_in, raw_out in example_pairs:\n459\t            h, w = len(raw_in), len(raw_in[0]) if raw_in else 0\n460\t            if h != len(raw_out) or w != len(raw_out[0] if raw_out else []):\n461\t                return None\n462\t\n463\t            in_colors = {c for row in raw_in for c in row}\n464\t            out_colors = {c for row in raw_out for c in row}\n465\t            new_colors = out_colors - in_colors\n466\t            if len(new_colors) != 1:\n467\t                return None\n468\t            m = next(iter(new_colors))\n469\t\n470\t            # Background = most-frequent color in input\n471\t            counts = {}\n472\t            for row in raw_in:\n473\t                for c in row:\n474\t                    counts[c] = counts.get(c, 0) + 1\n475\t            bg = max(counts, key=counts.get)\n476\t\n477\t            # Foreground = the other input color (must be exactly two)\n478\t            fg_set = {c for c in in_colors if c != bg}\n479\t            if len(fg_set) != 1:\n480\t                return None\n481\t            fg = next(iter(fg_set))\n482\t\n483\t            # Compute bbox of foreground in input\n484\t            rows = [r for r in range(h) for c in range(w) if raw_in[r][c] == fg]\n485\t            cols = [c for r in range(h) for c in range(w) if raw_in[r][c] == fg]\n486\t            if not rows:\n487\t                return None\n488\t            r0, r1 = min(rows), max(rows)\n489\t            c0, c1 = min(cols), max(cols)\n490\t\n491\t            # Verify: inside bbox, bg→marker, fg→fg; outside bbox unchanged\n492\t            for r in range(h):\n493\t                for c in range(w):\n494\t                    inside = r0 <= r <= r1 and c0 <= c <= c1\n495\t                    if inside and raw_in[r][c] == bg:\n496\t                        if raw_out[r][c] != m:\n497\t                            return None\n498\t                    else:\n499\t                        if raw_out[r][c] != raw_in[r][c]:\n500\t                            return None\n501\t\n502\t            if marker is None:\n503\t                marker, bg_color, fg_color = m, bg, fg\n504\t            elif (m, bg, fg) != (marker, bg_color, fg_color):\n505\t                return None\n506\t\n507\t        return {\n508\t            \"type\": \"bbox_fill\",\n509\t            \"marker\": marker,\n510\t            \"background\": bg_color,\n511\t            \"foreground\": fg_color,\n512\t            \"confidence\": 1.0,\n513\t        }\n514\t\n515\t    # ---- strategy: axis mirror recolor ----------------------------------\n516\t\n517\t    def _try_axis_mirror_recolor(self, example_pairs):\n518\t        \"\"\"\n519\t        Detect: same grid size, exactly one new color in output (marker).\n520\t        For some axis (horizontal/vertical), every changed cell is the\n521\t        original foreground color and its mirror partner along that axis\n522\t        also has the original foreground color in the input.\n523\t        Unchanged cells are those without a same-color mirror partner.\n524\t        \"\"\"\n525\t        if not example_pairs:\n526\t            return None\n527\t\n528\t        for axis in (\"horizontal\", \"vertical\"):\n529\t            params = self._check_mirror_axis(example_pairs, axis)\n530\t            if params is not None:\n531\t                return {\n532\t                    \"type\": \"axis_mirror_recolor\",\n533\t                    \"axis\": axis,\n534\t                    \"marker\": params[\"marker\"],\n535\t                    \"foreground\": params[\"foreground\"],\n536\t                    \"confidence\": 1.0,\n537\t                }\n538\t        return None\n539\t\n540\t    @staticmethod\n541\t    def _check_mirror_axis(example_pairs, axis):\n542\t        marker = None\n543\t        fg = None\n544\t        had_change = False\n545\t\n546\t        for raw_in, raw_out in example_pairs:\n547\t            h = len(raw_in)\n548\t            w = len(raw_in[0]) if raw_in else 0\n549\t            if h != len(raw_out) or (w and w != len(raw_out[0])):\n550\t                return None\n551\t\n552\t            new_colors = (\n553\t                {c for row in raw_out for c in row}\n554\t                - {c for row in raw_in for c in row}\n555\t            )\n556\t            if len(new_colors) != 1:\n557\t                return None\n558\t            m = next(iter(new_colors))\n559\t\n560\t            for r in range(h):\n561\t                for c in range(w):\n562\t                    if axis == \"horizontal\":\n563\t                        rr, cc = r, w - 1 - c\n564\t                    else:\n565\t                        rr, cc = h - 1 - r, c\n566\t                    in_v = raw_in[r][c]\n567\t                    out_v = raw_out[r][c]\n568\t                    mirror_v = raw_in[rr][cc]\n569\t                    if out_v == in_v:\n570\t                        # If this cell HAS a same-color mirror partner of\n571\t                        # a non-bg color, the rule would have flipped it.\n572\t                        # We require: not changed → no same-color partner\n573\t                        # OR cell is on the axis and equals itself (trivial).\n574\t                        if (r, c) != (rr, cc) and in_v == mirror_v and in_v != 0:\n575\t                            # only allow when in_v is the background\n576\t                            # (but bg already excluded by != 0 check is rough);\n577\t                            # we'll defer to fg check below.\n578\t                            pass\n579\t                        continue\n580\t                    # Changed: must change FROM some fg TO marker, with mirror\n581\t                    # partner also equal to fg in the input.\n582\t                    if out_v != m:\n583\t                        return None\n584\t                    if in_v == 0:\n585\t                        # background-cells turning into marker — not this rule\n586\t                        return None\n587\t                    if mirror_v != in_v:\n588\t                        return None\n589\t                    if fg is None:\n590\t                        fg = in_v\n591\t                    elif fg != in_v:\n592\t                        return None\n593\t                    had_change = True\n594\t\n595\t            if marker is None:\n596\t                marker = m\n597\t            elif marker != m:\n598\t                return None\n599\t\n600\t        if not had_change or fg is None:\n601\t            return None\n602\t\n603\t        # Final sanity: re-apply rule and confirm exact match.\n604\t        for raw_in, raw_out in example_pairs:\n605\t            h = len(raw_in)\n606\t            w = len(raw_in[0]) if raw_in else 0\n607\t            for r in range(h):\n608\t                for c in range(w):\n609\t                    if axis == \"horizontal\":\n610\t                        rr, cc = r, w - 1 - c\n611\t                    else:\n612\t                        rr, cc = h - 1 - r, c\n613\t                    expected = raw_in[r][c]\n614\t                    if (raw_in[r][c] == fg\n615\t                            and (r, c) != (rr, cc)\n616\t                            and raw_in[rr][cc] == fg):\n617\t                        expected = marker\n618\t                    if raw_out[r][c] != expected:\n619\t                        return None\n620\t\n621\t        return {\"marker\": marker, \"foreground\": fg}\n622\t\n623\t    # ---- strategy: integer upscale --------------------------------------\n624\t\n625\t    def _try_integer_upscale(self, example_pairs):\n626\t        \"\"\"\n627\t        Detect: output dimensions are k * input dimensions (same k for both\n628\t        height and width, and the same k across all examples). Each input\n629\t        cell at (r, c) becomes a kxk block at rows [k*r, k*r+k) and cols\n630\t        [k*c, k*c+k) in the output, all filled with the same color.\n631\t        \"\"\"\n632\t        if not example_pairs:\n633\t            return None\n634\t\n635\t        factor = None\n636\t        for raw_in, raw_out in example_pairs:\n637\t            ih = len(raw_in)\n638\t            iw = len(raw_in[0]) if raw_in else 0\n639\t            oh = len(raw_out)\n640\t            ow = len(raw_out[0]) if raw_out else 0\n641\t            if ih == 0 or iw == 0 or oh == 0 or ow == 0:\n642\t                return None\n643\t            if oh % ih != 0 or ow % iw != 0:\n644\t                return None\n645\t            kh, kw = oh // ih, ow // iw\n646\t            if kh != kw or kh < 2:\n647\t                return None\n648\t            if factor is None:\n649\t                factor = kh\n650\t            elif factor != kh:\n651\t                return None\n652\t            for r in range(ih):\n653\t                for c in range(iw):\n654\t                    v = raw_in[r][c]\n655\t                    for dr in range(factor):\n656\t                        for dc in range(factor):\n657\t                            if raw_out[r * factor + dr][c * factor + dc] != v:\n658\t                                return None\n659\t\n660\t        if factor is None:\n661\t            return None\n662\t        return {\"type\": \"integer_upscale\", \"factor\": factor, \"confidence\": 1.0}\n663\t\n664\t    # ---- strategy: stack with mirror ------------------------------------\n665\t\n666\t    def _try_stack_with_mirror(self, example_pairs):\n667\t        \"\"\"\n668\t        Detect: output = concatenation of input and a flipped copy of input\n669\t        along one axis. Tries four configurations:\n670\t          - direction=vertical,   order=input_first  (rows: input, vflip(input))\n671\t          - direction=vertical,   order=flip_first   (rows: vflip(input), input)\n672\t          - direction=horizontal, order=input_first  (cols: input, hflip(input))\n673\t          - direction=horizontal, order=flip_first   (cols: hflip(input), input)\n674\t        The same configuration must hold across every example.\n675\t        \"\"\"\n676\t        if not example_pairs:\n677\t            return None\n678\t\n679\t        configs = [\n680\t            (\"vertical\", \"input_first\"),\n681\t            (\"vertical\", \"flip_first\"),\n682\t            (\"horizontal\", \"input_first\"),\n683\t            (\"horizontal\", \"flip_first\"),\n684\t        ]\n685\t\n686\t        for direction, order in configs:\n687\t            ok = True\n688\t            for raw_in, raw_out in example_pairs:\n689\t                if not self._check_stack_mirror(raw_in, raw_out, direction, order):\n690\t                    ok = False\n691\t                    break\n692\t            if ok:\n693\t                return {\n694\t                    \"type\": \"stack_with_mirror\",\n695\t                    \"direction\": direction,\n696\t                    \"order\": order,\n697\t                    \"confidence\": 1.0,\n698\t                }\n699\t        return None\n700\t\n701\t    @staticmethod\n702\t    def _check_stack_mirror(raw_in, raw_out, direction, order):\n703\t        ih = len(raw_in)\n704\t        iw = len(raw_in[0]) if raw_in else 0\n705\t        oh = len(raw_out)\n706\t        ow = len(raw_out[0]) if raw_out else 0\n707\t        if ih == 0 or iw == 0:\n708\t            return False\n709\t\n710\t        if direction == \"vertical\":\n711\t            if ow != iw or oh != 2 * ih:\n712\t                return False\n713\t            flipped = list(reversed(raw_in))\n714\t            top = raw_in if order == \"input_first\" else flipped\n715\t            bot = flipped if order == \"input_first\" else raw_in\n716\t            for r in range(ih):\n717\t                if list(raw_out[r]) != list(top[r]):\n718\t                    return False\n719\t                if list(raw_out[ih + r]) != list(bot[r]):\n720\t                    return False\n721\t            return True\n722\t        else:  # horizontal\n723\t            if oh != ih or ow != 2 * iw:\n724\t                return False\n725\t            flipped = [list(reversed(row)) for row in raw_in]\n726\t            left = raw_in if order == \"input_first\" else flipped\n727\t            right = flipped if order == \"input_first\" else raw_in\n728\t            for r in range(ih):\n729\t                if list(raw_out[r][:iw]) != list(left[r]):\n730\t                    return False\n731\t                if list(raw_out[r][iw:]) != list(right[r]):\n732\t                    return False\n733\t            return True\n734\t\n735\t    # ---- strategy: rectangle interior fill ------------------------------\n736\t\n737\t    def _try_rect_interior_fill(self, example_pairs):\n738\t        \"\"\"\n739\t        Detect: same grid size; input contains hollow rectangular borders of a\n740\t        single foreground color on a background; output equals input except\n741\t        each hollow rect's interior is filled with a color determined by the\n742\t        rect's interior dimensions. Map (interior_h, interior_w) -> fill_color\n743\t        is learned from training and applied to test rectangles.\n744\t        \"\"\"\n745\t        if not example_pairs:\n746\t            return None\n747\t\n748\t        size_to_fill = {}\n749\t        bg_color = None\n750\t        border_color = None\n751\t\n752\t        for raw_in, raw_out in example_pairs:\n753\t            h = len(raw_in)\n754\t            w = len(raw_in[0]) if raw_in else 0\n755\t            if h == 0 or w == 0:\n756\t                return None\n757\t            if h != len(raw_out) or w != (len(raw_out[0]) if raw_out else 0):\n758\t                return None\n759\t\n760\t            # Background = most-frequent color in input\n761\t            counts = {}\n762\t            for row in raw_in:\n763\t                for c in row:\n764\t                    counts[c] = counts.get(c, 0) + 1\n765\t            bg = max(counts, key=counts.get)\n766\t\n767\t            # Foreground colors = everything else; require exactly one\n768\t            fg_set = {c for c in counts if c != bg}\n769\t            if len(fg_set) != 1:\n770\t                return None\n771\t            fg = next(iter(fg_set))\n772\t\n773\t            if bg_color is None:\n774\t                bg_color, border_color = bg, fg\n775\t            elif (bg_color, border_color) != (bg, fg):\n776\t                return None\n777\t\n778\t            rects = self._find_hollow_rects(raw_in, fg, bg)\n779\t            if not rects:\n780\t                return None\n781\t\n782\t            # Build expected output: copy input, fill each rect interior\n783\t            # with the color present in raw_out at the interior cells.\n784\t            for (r0, c0, r1, c1) in rects:\n785\t                ih_int = r1 - r0 - 1\n786\t                iw_int = c1 - c0 - 1\n787\t                if ih_int < 1 or iw_int < 1:\n788\t                    return None\n789\t                fill = raw_out[r0 + 1][c0 + 1]\n790\t                # Interior must be uniform fill color in output\n791\t                for r in range(r0 + 1, r1):\n792\t                    for c in range(c0 + 1, c1):\n793\t                        if raw_out[r][c] != fill:\n794\t                            return None\n795\t                key = (ih_int, iw_int)\n796\t                if key in size_to_fill and size_to_fill[key] != fill:\n797\t                    return None\n798\t                size_to_fill[key] = fill\n799\t\n800\t            # Verify all non-interior cells are unchanged\n801\t            interior_cells = set()\n802\t            for (r0, c0, r1, c1) in rects:\n803\t                for r in range(r0 + 1, r1):\n804\t                    for c in range(c0 + 1, c1):\n805\t                        interior_cells.add((r, c))\n806\t            for r in range(h):\n807\t                for c in range(w):\n808\t                    if (r, c) in interior_cells:\n809\t                        continue\n810\t                    if raw_in[r][c] != raw_out[r][c]:\n811\t                        return None\n812\t\n813\t        if not size_to_fill:\n814\t            return None\n815\t        return {\n816\t            \"type\": \"rect_interior_fill\",\n817\t            \"background\": bg_color,\n818\t            \"border\": border_color,\n819\t            \"size_to_fill\": {f\"{k[0]}x{k[1]}\": v for k, v in size_to_fill.items()},\n820\t            \"confidence\": 1.0,\n821\t        }\n822\t\n823\t    @staticmethod\n824\t    def _find_hollow_rects(raw, fg, bg):\n825\t        \"\"\"Find all hollow rectangles of color fg with interior color bg.\n826\t        Returns list of (r0, c0, r1, c1) bounding boxes.\"\"\"\n827\t        h = len(raw)\n828\t        w = len(raw[0]) if raw else 0\n829\t\n830\t        # Find connected components of fg cells (4-connected)\n831\t        visited = [[False] * w for _ in range(h)]\n832\t        rects = []\n833\t\n834\t        for r in range(h):\n835\t            for c in range(w):\n836\t                if raw[r][c] != fg or visited[r][c]:\n837\t                    continue\n838\t                # BFS\n839\t                comp = []\n840\t                queue = [(r, c)]\n841\t                while queue:\n842\t                    rr, cc = queue.pop(0)\n843\t                    if rr < 0 or rr >= h or cc < 0 or cc >= w:\n844\t                        continue\n845\t                    if visited[rr][cc] or raw[rr][cc] != fg:\n846\t                        continue\n847\t                    visited[rr][cc] = True\n848\t                    comp.append((rr, cc))\n849\t                    for dr, dc in [(-1, 0), (1, 0), (0, -1), (0, 1)]:\n850\t                        queue.append((rr + dr, cc + dc))\n851\t\n852\t                if not comp:\n853\t                    continue\n854\t                rs = [p[0] for p in comp]\n855\t                cs = [p[1] for p in comp]\n856\t                r0, r1 = min(rs), max(rs)\n857\t                c0, c1 = min(cs), max(cs)\n858\t                width = c1 - c0 + 1\n859\t                height = r1 - r0 + 1\n860\t                if width < 3 or height < 3:\n861\t                    continue\n862\t                # Check border is all fg\n863\t                comp_set = set(comp)\n864\t                ok = True\n865\t                for cc in range(c0, c1 + 1):\n866\t                    if (r0, cc) not in comp_set or (r1, cc) not in comp_set:\n867\t                        ok = False\n868\t                        break\n869\t                if ok:\n870\t                    for rr in range(r0, r1 + 1):\n871\t                        if (rr, c0) not in comp_set or (rr, c1) not in comp_set:\n872\t                            ok = False\n873\t                            break\n874\t                if not ok:\n875\t                    continue\n876\t                # Check interior is all bg\n877\t                for rr in range(r0 + 1, r1):\n878\t                    for cc in range(c0 + 1, c1):\n879\t                        if raw[rr][cc] != bg:\n880\t                            ok = False\n881\t                            break\n882\t                    if not ok:\n883\t                        break\n884\t                # Component must be exactly the border (no extra fg cells)\n885\t                expected_border_size = 2 * (height + width) - 4\n886\t                if ok and len(comp) == expected_border_size:\n887\t                    rects.append((r0, c0, r1, c1))\n888\t        return rects\n889\t\n890\t    # ---- strategy: staircase extend right -------------------------------\n891\t\n892\t    def _try_staircase_extend_right(self, example_pairs):\n893\t        \"\"\"\n894\t        Detect: every input is exactly one row of width w; output has\n895\t        oh = w // 2 rows and width w. Row 0 of the output equals the input;\n896\t        each subsequent row extends the colored prefix by one cell to the\n897\t        right (one more cell of the same fg color, rest background).\n898\t        \"\"\"\n899\t        if not example_pairs:\n900\t            return None\n901\t\n902\t        for raw_in, raw_out in example_pairs:\n903\t            if len(raw_in) != 1:\n904\t                return None\n905\t            w = len(raw_in[0])\n906\t            if w < 2:\n907\t                return None\n908\t            oh = len(raw_out)\n909\t            if oh != w // 2 or oh < 1:\n910\t                return None\n911\t            for row in raw_out:\n912\t                if len(row) != w:\n913\t                    return None\n914\t\n915\t            # The prefix color (fg) is the leftmost cell; the rest must be a\n916\t            # single different background color.\n917\t            row0 = list(raw_in[0])\n918\t            distinct = set(row0)\n919\t            if len(distinct) != 2:\n920\t                return None\n921\t            fg = row0[0]\n922\t            bg = next(v for v in distinct if v != fg)\n923\t\n924\t            n = 0\n925\t            while n < w and row0[n] == fg:\n926\t                n += 1\n927\t            if n == 0 or any(v != bg for v in row0[n:]):\n928\t                return None\n929\t\n930\t            # Verify each output row\n931\t            for i in range(oh):\n932\t                expected = [fg] * (n + i) + [bg] * (w - n - i)\n933\t                if list(raw_out[i]) != expected:\n934\t                    return None\n935\t\n936\t        return {\"type\": \"staircase_extend_right\", \"confidence\": 1.0}\n937\t\n938\t\n939\t# ======================================================================\n940\t# DescendOperator -- placeholder for deeper KG exploration\n941\t# ======================================================================\n942\t\n943\tclass DescendOperator(Operator):\n944\t    \"\"\"\n945\t    Placeholder: moves focus to a deeper KG level when current-level\n946\t    analysis is insufficient. Not yet needed for the basic pipeline.\n947\t    \"\"\"\n948\t\n949\t    def __init__(self):\n950\t        super().__init__(\"descend\")\n951\t\n952\t    def precondition(self, wm) -> bool:\n953\t        raise NotImplementedError(\"DescendOperator.precondition() not implemented.\")\n954\t\n955\t    def effect(self, wm):\n956\t        raise NotImplementedError(\"DescendOperator.effect() not implemented.\")\n957\t\n958\t\n959\t# ======================================================================\n960\t# PredictOperator -- apply rule to test input\n961\t# ======================================================================\n962\t\n963\tclass PredictOperator(Operator):\n964\t    \"\"\"\n965\t    Reads the best rule from active-rules and applies it to each test\n966\t    pair's input grid to produce a predicted output grid.\n967\t    \"\"\"\n968\t\n969\t    def __init__(self):\n970\t        super().__init__(\"predict\")\n971\t\n972\t    def precondition(self, wm) -> bool:\n973\t        raise NotImplementedError(\"PredictOperator.precondition() not implemented.\")\n974\t\n975\t    def effect(self, wm):\n976\t        task = wm.task\n977\t        active_rules = wm.s1.get(\"active-rules\")\n978\t        if not task or not active_rules:\n979\t            return\n980\t\n981\t        rule = active_rules[0]\n982\t        predictions = dict(wm.s1.get(\"predictions\") or {})\n983\t\n984\t        for i, test_pair in enumerate(task.test_pairs):\n985\t            key = f\"test_{i}\"\n986\t            if key in predictions:\n987\t                continue\n988\t            g0 = test_pair.input_grid\n989\t            if g0 is None:\n990\t                continue\n991\t            predicted = self._apply_rule(rule, g0)\n992\t            if predicted is not None:\n993\t                predictions[key] = predicted\n994\t\n995\t        wm.s1[\"predictions\"] = predictions\n996\t\n997\t    # ---- rule application dispatchers ------------------------------------\n998\t\n999\t    def _apply_rule(self, rule, input_grid):\n1000\t        rule_type = rule.get(\"type\")\n1001\t        if rule_type == \"recolor_sequential\":\n1002\t            return self._apply_recolor_sequential(rule, input_grid)\n1003\t        if rule_type == \"color_mapping\":\n1004\t            return self._apply_color_mapping(rule, input_grid)\n1005\t        if rule_type == \"bbox_fill\":\n1006\t            return self._apply_bbox_fill(rule, input_grid)\n1007\t        if rule_type == \"axis_mirror_recolor\":\n1008\t            return self._apply_axis_mirror_recolor(rule, input_grid)\n1009\t        if rule_type == \"integer_upscale\":\n1010\t            return self._apply_integer_upscale(rule, input_grid)\n1011\t        if rule_type == \"stack_with_mirror\":\n1012\t            return self._apply_stack_with_mirror(rule, input_grid)\n1013\t        if rule_type == \"rect_interior_fill\":\n1014\t            return self._apply_rect_interior_fill(rule, input_grid)\n1015\t        if rule_type == \"staircase_extend_right\":\n1016\t            return self._apply_staircase_extend_right(rule, input_grid)\n1017\t        if rule_type == \"identity\":\n1018\t            return [row[:] for row in input_grid.raw]\n1019\t        return None\n1020\t\n1021\t    def _apply_recolor_sequential(self, rule, input_grid):\n1022\t        raw = input_grid.raw\n1023\t        height = len(raw)\n1024\t        width = len(raw[0]) if raw else 0\n1025\t        sort_key = rule[\"sort_key\"]\n1026\t        start_color = rule[\"start_color\"]\n1027\t        source_colors = set(rule.get(\"source_colors\", []))\n1028\t\n1029\t        # Find target cells\n1030\t        target_cells = []\n1031\t        for r in range(height):\n1032\t            for c in range(width):\n1033\t                if raw[r][c] in source_colors:\n1034\t                    target_cells.append((r, c))\n1035\t\n1036\t        if not target_cells:\n1037\t            return [row[:] for row in raw]\n1038\t\n1039\t        # Group into connected components\n1040\t        groups = self._group_positions(target_cells)\n1041\t\n1042\t        # Sort groups by the rule's sort key\n1043\t        def _sort_val(group):\n1044\t            if sort_key == \"top_row\":\n1045\t                return min(r for r, c in group)\n1046\t            if sort_key == \"top_col\":\n1047\t                return min(c for r, c in group)\n1048\t            return 0\n1049\t\n1050\t        sorted_groups = sorted(groups, key=_sort_val)\n1051\t\n1052\t        # Build output grid\n1053\t        output = [row[:] for row in raw]\n1054\t        for idx, group in enumerate(sorted_groups):\n1055\t            new_color = start_color + idx\n1056\t            for r, c in group:\n1057\t                output[r][c] = new_color\n1058\t\n1059\t        return output\n1060\t\n1061\t    def _apply_color_mapping(self, rule, input_grid):\n1062\t        raw = input_grid.raw\n1063\t        mapping = rule.get(\"mapping\", {})\n1064\t\n1065\t        output = []\n1066\t        for row in raw:\n1067\t            output.append([mapping.get(cell, cell) for cell in row])\n1068\t        return output\n1069\t\n1070\t    def _apply_bbox_fill(self, rule, input_grid):\n1071\t        raw = input_grid.raw\n1072\t        h = len(raw)\n1073\t        w = len(raw[0]) if raw else 0\n1074\t        marker = rule.get(\"marker\")\n1075\t        fg = rule.get(\"foreground\")\n1076\t        bg = rule.get(\"background\")\n1077\t        if marker is None or fg is None or bg is None:\n1078\t            return None\n1079\t\n1080\t        rows = [r for r in range(h) for c in range(w) if raw[r][c] == fg]\n1081\t        cols = [c for r in range(h) for c in range(w) if raw[r][c] == fg]\n1082\t        if not rows:\n1083\t            return [row[:] for row in raw]\n1084\t        r0, r1 = min(rows), max(rows)\n1085\t        c0, c1 = min(cols), max(cols)\n1086\t\n1087\t        out = [row[:] for row in raw]\n1088\t        for r in range(r0, r1 + 1):\n1089\t            for c in range(c0, c1 + 1):\n1090\t                if out[r][c] == bg:\n1091\t                    out[r][c] = marker\n1092\t        return out\n1093\t\n1094\t    def _apply_axis_mirror_recolor(self, rule, input_grid):\n1095\t        raw = input_grid.raw\n1096\t        h = len(raw)\n1097\t        w = len(raw[0]) if raw else 0\n1098\t        marker = rule.get(\"marker\")\n1099\t        fg = rule.get(\"foreground\")\n1100\t        axis = rule.get(\"axis\", \"horizontal\")\n1101\t        if marker is None or fg is None:\n1102\t            return None\n1103\t\n1104\t        out = [row[:] for row in raw]\n1105\t        for r in range(h):\n1106\t            for c in range(w):\n1107\t                if raw[r][c] != fg:\n1108\t                    continue\n1109\t                if axis == \"horizontal\":\n1110\t                    rr, cc = r, w - 1 - c\n1111\t                else:\n1112\t                    rr, cc = h - 1 - r, c\n1113\t                if (r, c) == (rr, cc):\n1114\t                    continue\n1115\t                if raw[rr][cc] == fg:\n1116\t                    out[r][c] = marker\n1117\t        return out\n1118\t\n1119\t    def _apply_integer_upscale(self, rule, input_grid):\n1120\t        raw = input_grid.raw\n1121\t        k = rule.get(\"factor\")\n1122\t        if not isinstance(k, int) or k < 2:\n1123\t            return None\n1124\t        out = []\n1125\t        for row in raw:\n1126\t            new_row = []\n1127\t            for v in row:\n1128\t                new_row.extend([v] * k)\n1129\t            for _ in range(k):\n1130\t                out.append(new_row[:])\n1131\t        return out\n1132\t\n1133\t    def _apply_stack_with_mirror(self, rule, input_grid):\n1134\t        raw = input_grid.raw\n1135\t        direction = rule.get(\"direction\")\n1136\t        order = rule.get(\"order\")\n1137\t        if direction not in (\"vertical\", \"horizontal\"):\n1138\t            return None\n1139\t        if order not in (\"input_first\", \"flip_first\"):\n1140\t            return None\n1141\t\n1142\t        if direction == \"vertical\":\n1143\t            flipped = list(reversed([row[:] for row in raw]))\n1144\t            top = [row[:] for row in raw] if order == \"input_first\" else flipped\n1145\t            bot = flipped if order == \"input_first\" else [row[:] for row in raw]\n1146\t            return [r[:] for r in top] + [r[:] for r in bot]\n1147\t        else:\n1148\t            flipped = [list(reversed(row)) for row in raw]\n1149\t            left = [row[:] for row in raw] if order == \"input_first\" else flipped\n1150\t            right = flipped if order == \"input_first\" else [row[:] for row in raw]\n1151\t            return [list(left[r]) + list(right[r]) for r in range(len(raw))]\n1152\t\n1153\t    def _apply_rect_interior_fill(self, rule, input_grid):\n1154\t        raw = input_grid.raw\n1155\t        h = len(raw)\n1156\t        w = len(raw[0]) if raw else 0\n1157\t        bg = rule.get(\"background\")\n1158\t        fg = rule.get(\"border\")\n1159\t        size_to_fill_raw = rule.get(\"size_to_fill\") or {}\n1160\t        if bg is None or fg is None:\n1161\t            return None\n1162\t        size_to_fill = {}\n1163\t        for k, v in size_to_fill_raw.items():\n1164\t            try:\n1165\t                a, b = k.split(\"x\")\n1166\t                size_to_fill[(int(a), int(b))] = v\n1167\t            except ValueError:\n1168\t                continue\n1169\t\n1170\t        rects = GeneralizeOperator._find_hollow_rects(raw, fg, bg)\n1171\t        out = [row[:] for row in raw]\n1172\t        for (r0, c0, r1, c1) in rects:\n1173\t            ih = r1 - r0 - 1\n1174\t            iw = c1 - c0 - 1\n1175\t            fill = size_to_fill.get((ih, iw))\n1176\t            if fill is None:\n1177\t                continue\n1178\t            for r in range(r0 + 1, r1):\n1179\t                for c in range(c0 + 1, c1):\n1180\t                    out[r][c] = fill\n1181\t        return out\n1182\t\n1183\t    def _apply_staircase_extend_right(self, rule, input_grid):\n1184\t        raw = input_grid.raw\n1185\t        if len(raw) != 1:\n1186\t            return None\n1187\t        row0 = list(raw[0])\n1188\t        w = len(row0)\n1189\t        if w < 2:\n1190\t            return None\n1191\t        distinct = set(row0)\n1192\t        if len(distinct) != 2:\n1193\t            return None\n1194\t        fg = row0[0]\n1195\t        bg = next(v for v in distinct if v != fg)\n1196\t        n = 0\n1197\t        while n < w and row0[n] == fg:\n1198\t            n += 1\n1199\t        if n == 0 or any(v != bg for v in row0[n:]):\n1200\t            return None\n1201\t        oh = w // 2\n1202\t        out = []\n1203\t        for i in range(oh):\n1204\t            cells = [fg] * (n + i) + [bg] * (w - n - i)\n1205\t            out.append(cells)\n1206\t        return out\n1207\t\n1208\t    # ---- helpers ---------------------------------------------------------\n1209\t\n1210\t    @staticmethod\n1211\t    def _group_positions(positions):\n1212\t        \"\"\"Group (row, col) positions into 4-connected components.\"\"\"\n1213\t        pos_set = set(positions)\n1214\t        visited = set()\n1215\t        groups = []\n1216\t\n1217\t        for pos in positions:\n1218\t            if pos in visited:\n1219\t                continue\n1220\t            group = []\n1221\t            queue = [pos]\n1222\t            while queue:\n1223\t                p = queue.pop(0)\n1224\t                if p in visited or p not in pos_set:\n1225\t                    continue\n1226\t                visited.add(p)\n1227\t                group.append(p)\n1228\t                r, c = p\n1229\t                for dr, dc in [(-1, 0), (1, 0), (0, -1), (0, 1)]:\n1230\t                    nb = (r + dr, c + dc)\n1231\t                    if nb in pos_set and nb not in visited:\n1232\t                        queue.append(nb)\n1233\t            groups.append(group)\n1234\t\n1235\t        return groups\n1236\t\n1237\t\n1238\t# ======================================================================\n1239\t# SubmitOperator -- finalize and satisfy goal\n1240\t# ======================================================================\n1241\t\n1242\tclass SubmitOperator(Operator):\n1243\t    \"\"\"\n1244\t    Writes predicted grids to S1 output-link in the format expected by\n1245\t    run_task.py, and marks the goal as satisfied.\n1246\t    \"\"\"\n1247\t\n1248\t    def __init__(self):\n1249\t        super().__init__(\"submit\")\n1250\t\n1251\t    def precondition(self, wm) -> bool:\n1252\t        raise NotImplementedError(\"SubmitOperator.precondition() not implemented.\")\n1253\t\n1254\t    def effect(self, wm):\n1255\t        predictions = wm.s1.get(\"predictions\")\n1256\t        if not predictions:\n1257\t            return\n1258\t\n1259\t        task = wm.task\n1260\t        if not task:\n1261\t            return\n1262\t\n1263\t        predicted_grids = []\n1264\t        for i in range(len(task.test_pairs)):\n1265\t            grid = predictions.get(f\"test_{i}\")\n1266\t            if grid is not None:\n1267\t                predicted_grids.append(grid)\n1268\t\n1269\t        if not predicted_grids:\n1270\t            return\n1271\t\n1272\t        # Write to output-link (format expected by run_task.py)\n1273\t        wm.s1[\"S1\"] = {\"output-link\": \"O_out\"}\n1274\t        wm.s1[\"O_out\"] = {\"predicted-grid\": predicted_grids}\n1275\t\n1276\t        # Mark goal as satisfied\n1277\t        wm.s1[\"goal\"] = {\"subgoals\": {\n1278\t            f\"test_{i}\": {\"status\": \"solved\"}\n1279\t            for i in range(len(predicted_grids))\n1280\t        }}\n1281\t\n1282\t\n1283\tclass VerifyOperator(SubmitOperator):\n1284\t    \"\"\"Alias for the verify operation (same mechanism as submit).\"\"\"\n1285\t\n1286\t    def __init__(self):\n1287\t        super().__init__()\n1288\t        self.name = \"verify\"\n1289\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"3fed7f85-792d-4d37-88c2-f10a44b2632b","uuid":"e8010755-1012-468e-b455-54f6ff813139","timestamp":"2026-04-28T22:59:06.208Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/Users/sir_k/Desktop/SOAR-ARC-test/agent/active_operators.py","content":"\"\"\"\nactive_operators -- SOAR Operator implementations.\n\nPipeline operators (all fire in S2, read/write S1):\n  SelectTargetOperator  -> set up comparison agenda from example pairs\n  CompareOperator       -> execute one comparison using ARCKG compare()\n  ExtractPatternOperator-> cell-level analysis of input/output changes\n  GeneralizeOperator    -> create transformation rule from patterns\n  PredictOperator       -> apply rule to test input\n  SubmitOperator        -> write prediction to output-link, satisfy goal\n\"\"\"\n\nfrom agent.operators import Operator\nfrom ARCKG.comparison import compare as arckg_compare\n\n\n# ======================================================================\n# SolveTaskOperator -- abstract top-level goal (S1)\n# ======================================================================\n\nclass SolveTaskOperator(Operator):\n    \"\"\"\n    Abstract operator at S1. Intentionally makes no WM change so\n    the cycle detects no-change and creates an S2 substate.\n    \"\"\"\n\n    def __init__(self):\n        super().__init__(\"solve-task\")\n        self.proposal_preference = \"+\"\n\n    def precondition(self, wm) -> bool:\n        raise NotImplementedError(\"SolveTaskOperator.precondition() not implemented.\")\n\n    def effect(self, wm):\n        # Intentionally empty -- triggers no-change impasse -> S2\n        return\n\n\n# ======================================================================\n# SelectTargetOperator -- set up comparison agenda\n# ======================================================================\n\nclass SelectTargetOperator(Operator):\n    \"\"\"\n    Reads wm.task to find example pairs and sets up comparison targets.\n    For each example pair: compare input grid (G0) vs output grid (G1).\n    Writes comparison-agenda, pending-comparisons, and empty comparisons to S1.\n    \"\"\"\n\n    def __init__(self):\n        super().__init__(\"select_target\")\n\n    def precondition(self, wm) -> bool:\n        raise NotImplementedError(\"SelectTargetOperator.precondition() not implemented.\")\n\n    def effect(self, wm):\n        task = wm.task\n        if task is None:\n            return\n\n        agenda = []\n        pending = []\n\n        for idx, pair in enumerate(task.example_pairs):\n            if pair.input_grid is not None and pair.output_grid is not None:\n                spec = {\n                    \"type\": \"grid\",\n                    \"pair_idx\": idx,\n                    \"pair_type\": \"example\",\n                    \"id1\": pair.input_grid.node_id,\n                    \"id2\": pair.output_grid.node_id,\n                }\n                agenda.append(spec)\n                pending.append(spec)\n\n        # Build node lookup so CompareOperator can find ARCKG nodes by ID\n        node_lookup = {}\n        for pair in task.example_pairs + task.test_pairs:\n            if pair.input_grid:\n                node_lookup[pair.input_grid.node_id] = pair.input_grid\n            if pair.output_grid:\n                node_lookup[pair.output_grid.node_id] = pair.output_grid\n        wm.node_lookup = node_lookup\n\n        wm.s1[\"comparison-agenda\"] = agenda\n        wm.s1[\"pending-comparisons\"] = pending\n        wm.s1[\"comparisons\"] = {}\n\n\n# ======================================================================\n# CompareOperator -- execute one comparison\n# ======================================================================\n\nclass CompareOperator(Operator):\n    \"\"\"\n    Pops one item from pending-comparisons, calls ARCKG compare(),\n    and stores the result in the comparisons dict on S1.\n    \"\"\"\n\n    def __init__(self, compare_fn=None):\n        super().__init__(\"compare\")\n        self._compare_fn = compare_fn\n\n    def precondition(self, wm) -> bool:\n        raise NotImplementedError(\"CompareOperator.precondition() not implemented.\")\n\n    def effect(self, wm):\n        pending = list(wm.s1.get(\"pending-comparisons\") or [])\n        if not pending:\n            return\n\n        item = pending.pop(0)\n\n        # Find the actual ARCKG nodes\n        node_lookup = getattr(wm, \"node_lookup\", {})\n        node_a = node_lookup.get(item[\"id1\"])\n        node_b = node_lookup.get(item[\"id2\"])\n\n        if node_a is None or node_b is None:\n            wm.s1[\"pending-comparisons\"] = pending\n            return\n\n        # Execute comparison\n        fn = self._compare_fn or arckg_compare\n        result = fn(node_a, node_b)\n\n        # Store result keyed by type and pair index\n        key = f\"{item['type']}_{item.get('pair_idx', 0)}\"\n        comparisons = dict(wm.s1.get(\"comparisons\") or {})\n        comparisons[key] = {\"spec\": item, \"result\": result}\n\n        wm.s1[\"pending-comparisons\"] = pending\n        wm.s1[\"comparisons\"] = comparisons\n\n\n# ======================================================================\n# ExtractPatternOperator -- cell-level transformation analysis\n# ======================================================================\n\nclass ExtractPatternOperator(Operator):\n    \"\"\"\n    Analyzes each example pair at the cell level to discover what changes\n    between input and output grids. Groups changed cells into connected\n    components and records color/position information for generalization.\n    \"\"\"\n\n    def __init__(self):\n        super().__init__(\"extract_pattern\")\n\n    def precondition(self, wm) -> bool:\n        raise NotImplementedError(\"ExtractPatternOperator.precondition() not implemented.\")\n\n    def effect(self, wm):\n        task = wm.task\n        if task is None:\n            return\n\n        patterns = {\n            \"grid_size_preserved\": True,\n            \"pair_analyses\": [],\n        }\n\n        for pair in task.example_pairs:\n            g0 = pair.input_grid\n            g1 = pair.output_grid\n            if g0 is None or g1 is None:\n                continue\n\n            analysis = self._analyze_pair(g0, g1)\n            patterns[\"pair_analyses\"].append(analysis)\n\n            if g0.height != g1.height or g0.width != g1.width:\n                patterns[\"grid_size_preserved\"] = False\n\n        wm.s1[\"patterns\"] = patterns\n\n    # ---- internal helpers ------------------------------------------------\n\n    def _analyze_pair(self, g0, g1):\n        \"\"\"Cell-level diff between input and output grid.\"\"\"\n        raw_in = g0.raw\n        raw_out = g1.raw\n        h = min(len(raw_in), len(raw_out))\n        w = min(\n            len(raw_in[0]) if raw_in else 0,\n            len(raw_out[0]) if raw_out else 0,\n        )\n\n        changes = []\n        for r in range(h):\n            for c in range(w):\n                if raw_in[r][c] != raw_out[r][c]:\n                    changes.append({\n                        \"row\": r, \"col\": c,\n                        \"input_color\": raw_in[r][c],\n                        \"output_color\": raw_out[r][c],\n                    })\n\n        groups = self._group_changes(changes)\n\n        group_analyses = []\n        for group_cells in groups:\n            input_colors = set()\n            output_colors = set()\n            positions = []\n            for cell in group_cells:\n                input_colors.add(cell[\"input_color\"])\n                output_colors.add(cell[\"output_color\"])\n                positions.append((cell[\"row\"], cell[\"col\"]))\n\n            top_row = min(r for r, c in positions)\n            top_col = min(c for r, c in positions)\n\n            group_analyses.append({\n                \"input_colors\": sorted(input_colors),\n                \"output_colors\": sorted(output_colors),\n                \"top_row\": top_row,\n                \"top_col\": top_col,\n                \"cell_count\": len(group_cells),\n            })\n\n        return {\n            \"total_changes\": len(changes),\n            \"num_groups\": len(groups),\n            \"groups\": group_analyses,\n            \"size_match\": (\n                len(raw_in) == len(raw_out)\n                and (len(raw_in[0]) if raw_in else 0)\n                    == (len(raw_out[0]) if raw_out else 0)\n            ),\n        }\n\n    @staticmethod\n    def _group_changes(changes):\n        \"\"\"Group changed cells into 4-connected components.\"\"\"\n        if not changes:\n            return []\n\n        pos_to_change = {}\n        for c in changes:\n            pos_to_change[(c[\"row\"], c[\"col\"])] = c\n\n        visited = set()\n        groups = []\n\n        for change in changes:\n            pos = (change[\"row\"], change[\"col\"])\n            if pos in visited:\n                continue\n\n            group = []\n            queue = [pos]\n            while queue:\n                p = queue.pop(0)\n                if p in visited or p not in pos_to_change:\n                    continue\n                visited.add(p)\n                group.append(pos_to_change[p])\n                for dr, dc in [(-1, 0), (1, 0), (0, -1), (0, 1)]:\n                    nb = (p[0] + dr, p[1] + dc)\n                    if nb in pos_to_change and nb not in visited:\n                        queue.append(nb)\n            groups.append(group)\n\n        return groups\n\n\n# ======================================================================\n# GeneralizeOperator -- rule creation from patterns\n# ======================================================================\n\nclass GeneralizeOperator(Operator):\n    \"\"\"\n    Reads extracted patterns and attempts to create a transformation rule.\n    Tries multiple strategies in priority order. If no strategy succeeds,\n    falls back to an identity rule so the pipeline can still complete.\n    \"\"\"\n\n    def __init__(self, generalize_fn=None, save_fn=None):\n        super().__init__(\"generalize\")\n        self._generalize_fn = generalize_fn\n        self._save_fn = save_fn\n\n    def precondition(self, wm) -> bool:\n        raise NotImplementedError(\"GeneralizeOperator.precondition() not implemented.\")\n\n    def effect(self, wm):\n        patterns = wm.s1.get(\"patterns\")\n        if not patterns:\n            return\n\n        task = wm.task\n        example_pairs = self._collect_example_pairs(task)\n\n        rule = None\n\n        # Strategy 1: sequential recoloring (e.g., color objects 1, 2, 3, ...)\n        rule = self._try_recolor_sequential(patterns)\n\n        # Strategy 2: bounding-box fill — fill bg cells within bbox of fg color\n        if rule is None:\n            rule = self._try_bbox_fill(example_pairs)\n\n        # Strategy 3: horizontal mirror recolor — recolor cells whose\n        #   horizontal-mirror partner has the same color\n        if rule is None:\n            rule = self._try_axis_mirror_recolor(example_pairs)\n\n        # Strategy 4: integer upscale — each input cell becomes a kxk block\n        if rule is None:\n            rule = self._try_integer_upscale(example_pairs)\n\n        # Strategy 5: stack with mirror — output = concat(input, flip(input))\n        if rule is None:\n            rule = self._try_stack_with_mirror(example_pairs)\n\n        # Strategy 6: rectangle interior fill — hollow rect borders get interior\n        #   filled with a color determined by interior dimensions\n        if rule is None:\n            rule = self._try_rect_interior_fill(example_pairs)\n\n        # Strategy 7: staircase extend right — 1-row input becomes a triangular\n        #   stack of rows where each row's prefix grows by one cell\n        if rule is None:\n            rule = self._try_staircase_extend_right(example_pairs)\n\n        # Strategy 8: simple 1:1 color mapping\n        if rule is None:\n            rule = self._try_color_mapping(patterns)\n\n        # Fallback: identity (copy input as output)\n        if rule is None:\n            rule = {\"type\": \"identity\", \"confidence\": 0.0}\n\n        wm.s1[\"active-rules\"] = [rule]\n\n    @staticmethod\n    def _collect_example_pairs(task):\n        \"\"\"Return list of (raw_input, raw_output) tuples for example pairs.\"\"\"\n        if task is None:\n            return []\n        out = []\n        for pair in task.example_pairs:\n            g0, g1 = pair.input_grid, pair.output_grid\n            if g0 is None or g1 is None:\n                continue\n            out.append((g0.raw, g1.raw))\n        return out\n\n    # ---- strategy: sequential recoloring --------------------------------\n\n    def _try_recolor_sequential(self, patterns):\n        \"\"\"\n        Detect pattern: all changed-cell groups have one source color,\n        output colors are sequential (1,2,3,...), ordered by position.\n        \"\"\"\n        pair_analyses = patterns.get(\"pair_analyses\", [])\n        if not pair_analyses or not patterns.get(\"grid_size_preserved\"):\n            return None\n\n        # All pairs must have the same number of change groups\n        group_counts = [a[\"num_groups\"] for a in pair_analyses]\n        if len(set(group_counts)) != 1 or group_counts[0] == 0:\n            return None\n\n        all_source_colors = set()\n\n        for analysis in pair_analyses:\n            for g in analysis[\"groups\"]:\n                if len(g[\"input_colors\"]) != 1 or len(g[\"output_colors\"]) != 1:\n                    return None\n                all_source_colors.add(g[\"input_colors\"][0])\n\n            out_colors = sorted(set(g[\"output_colors\"][0] for g in analysis[\"groups\"]))\n            expected = list(range(min(out_colors), min(out_colors) + len(out_colors)))\n            if out_colors != expected:\n                return None\n\n        # Try sorting by different position keys\n        for sort_key in [\"top_row\", \"top_col\"]:\n            if self._check_sort_key(pair_analyses, sort_key):\n                start_color = min(\n                    g[\"output_colors\"][0]\n                    for g in pair_analyses[0][\"groups\"]\n                )\n                return {\n                    \"type\": \"recolor_sequential\",\n                    \"sort_key\": sort_key,\n                    \"start_color\": start_color,\n                    \"source_colors\": sorted(all_source_colors),\n                    \"confidence\": 1.0,\n                }\n\n        return None\n\n    @staticmethod\n    def _check_sort_key(pair_analyses, sort_key):\n        \"\"\"Verify that sorting groups by sort_key produces sequential output colors.\"\"\"\n        for analysis in pair_analyses:\n            groups = analysis[\"groups\"]\n            sorted_groups = sorted(groups, key=lambda g: g[sort_key])\n            colors = [g[\"output_colors\"][0] for g in sorted_groups]\n            if colors != list(range(colors[0], colors[0] + len(colors))):\n                return False\n        return True\n\n    # ---- strategy: simple color mapping ---------------------------------\n\n    def _try_color_mapping(self, patterns):\n        \"\"\"\n        Detect pattern: each input color consistently maps to one output color.\n        \"\"\"\n        pair_analyses = patterns.get(\"pair_analyses\", [])\n        if not pair_analyses or not patterns.get(\"grid_size_preserved\"):\n            return None\n\n        # Collect all observed color transitions\n        color_map = {}\n        for analysis in pair_analyses:\n            for group in analysis[\"groups\"]:\n                for ic in group[\"input_colors\"]:\n                    for oc in group[\"output_colors\"]:\n                        if ic not in color_map:\n                            color_map[ic] = set()\n                        color_map[ic].add(oc)\n\n        # Each input color must map to exactly one output color\n        simple_map = {}\n        for ic, ocs in color_map.items():\n            if len(ocs) != 1:\n                return None\n            simple_map[ic] = list(ocs)[0]\n\n        if simple_map:\n            return {\n                \"type\": \"color_mapping\",\n                \"mapping\": simple_map,\n                \"confidence\": 0.8,\n            }\n\n        return None\n\n    # ---- strategy: bounding-box fill ------------------------------------\n\n    def _try_bbox_fill(self, example_pairs):\n        \"\"\"\n        Detect: same grid size; output equals input except every background\n        cell within the bounding box of the foreground color has been\n        recolored to a single marker color (a color not present in input).\n        \"\"\"\n        if not example_pairs:\n            return None\n\n        marker = None\n        bg_color = None\n        fg_color = None\n\n        for raw_in, raw_out in example_pairs:\n            h, w = len(raw_in), len(raw_in[0]) if raw_in else 0\n            if h != len(raw_out) or w != len(raw_out[0] if raw_out else []):\n                return None\n\n            in_colors = {c for row in raw_in for c in row}\n            out_colors = {c for row in raw_out for c in row}\n            new_colors = out_colors - in_colors\n            if len(new_colors) != 1:\n                return None\n            m = next(iter(new_colors))\n\n            # Background = most-frequent color in input\n            counts = {}\n            for row in raw_in:\n                for c in row:\n                    counts[c] = counts.get(c, 0) + 1\n            bg = max(counts, key=counts.get)\n\n            # Foreground = the other input color (must be exactly two)\n            fg_set = {c for c in in_colors if c != bg}\n            if len(fg_set) != 1:\n                return None\n            fg = next(iter(fg_set))\n\n            # Compute bbox of foreground in input\n            rows = [r for r in range(h) for c in range(w) if raw_in[r][c] == fg]\n            cols = [c for r in range(h) for c in range(w) if raw_in[r][c] == fg]\n            if not rows:\n                return None\n            r0, r1 = min(rows), max(rows)\n            c0, c1 = min(cols), max(cols)\n\n            # Verify: inside bbox, bg→marker, fg→fg; outside bbox unchanged\n            for r in range(h):\n                for c in range(w):\n                    inside = r0 <= r <= r1 and c0 <= c <= c1\n                    if inside and raw_in[r][c] == bg:\n                        if raw_out[r][c] != m:\n                            return None\n                    else:\n                        if raw_out[r][c] != raw_in[r][c]:\n                            return None\n\n            if marker is None:\n                marker, bg_color, fg_color = m, bg, fg\n            elif (m, bg, fg) != (marker, bg_color, fg_color):\n                return None\n\n        return {\n            \"type\": \"bbox_fill\",\n            \"marker\": marker,\n            \"background\": bg_color,\n            \"foreground\": fg_color,\n            \"confidence\": 1.0,\n        }\n\n    # ---- strategy: axis mirror recolor ----------------------------------\n\n    def _try_axis_mirror_recolor(self, example_pairs):\n        \"\"\"\n        Detect: same grid size, exactly one new color in output (marker).\n        For some axis (horizontal/vertical), every changed cell is the\n        original foreground color and its mirror partner along that axis\n        also has the original foreground color in the input.\n        Unchanged cells are those without a same-color mirror partner.\n        \"\"\"\n        if not example_pairs:\n            return None\n\n        for axis in (\"horizontal\", \"vertical\"):\n            params = self._check_mirror_axis(example_pairs, axis)\n            if params is not None:\n                return {\n                    \"type\": \"axis_mirror_recolor\",\n                    \"axis\": axis,\n                    \"marker\": params[\"marker\"],\n                    \"foreground\": params[\"foreground\"],\n                    \"confidence\": 1.0,\n                }\n        return None\n\n    @staticmethod\n    def _check_mirror_axis(example_pairs, axis):\n        marker = None\n        fg = None\n        had_change = False\n\n        for raw_in, raw_out in example_pairs:\n            h = len(raw_in)\n            w = len(raw_in[0]) if raw_in else 0\n            if h != len(raw_out) or (w and w != len(raw_out[0])):\n                return None\n\n            new_colors = (\n                {c for row in raw_out for c in row}\n                - {c for row in raw_in for c in row}\n            )\n            if len(new_colors) != 1:\n                return None\n            m = next(iter(new_colors))\n\n            for r in range(h):\n                for c in range(w):\n                    if axis == \"horizontal\":\n                        rr, cc = r, w - 1 - c\n                    else:\n                        rr, cc = h - 1 - r, c\n                    in_v = raw_in[r][c]\n                    out_v = raw_out[r][c]\n                    mirror_v = raw_in[rr][cc]\n                    if out_v == in_v:\n                        # If this cell HAS a same-color mirror partner of\n                        # a non-bg color, the rule would have flipped it.\n                        # We require: not changed → no same-color partner\n                        # OR cell is on the axis and equals itself (trivial).\n                        if (r, c) != (rr, cc) and in_v == mirror_v and in_v != 0:\n                            # only allow when in_v is the background\n                            # (but bg already excluded by != 0 check is rough);\n                            # we'll defer to fg check below.\n                            pass\n                        continue\n                    # Changed: must change FROM some fg TO marker, with mirror\n                    # partner also equal to fg in the input.\n                    if out_v != m:\n                        return None\n                    if in_v == 0:\n                        # background-cells turning into marker — not this rule\n                        return None\n                    if mirror_v != in_v:\n                        return None\n                    if fg is None:\n                        fg = in_v\n                    elif fg != in_v:\n                        return None\n                    had_change = True\n\n            if marker is None:\n                marker = m\n            elif marker != m:\n                return None\n\n        if not had_change or fg is None:\n            return None\n\n        # Final sanity: re-apply rule and confirm exact match.\n        for raw_in, raw_out in example_pairs:\n            h = len(raw_in)\n            w = len(raw_in[0]) if raw_in else 0\n            for r in range(h):\n                for c in range(w):\n                    if axis == \"horizontal\":\n                        rr, cc = r, w - 1 - c\n                    else:\n                        rr, cc = h - 1 - r, c\n                    expected = raw_in[r][c]\n                    if (raw_in[r][c] == fg\n                            and (r, c) != (rr, cc)\n                            and raw_in[rr][cc] == fg):\n                        expected = marker\n                    if raw_out[r][c] != expected:\n                        return None\n\n        return {\"marker\": marker, \"foreground\": fg}\n\n    # ---- strategy: integer upscale --------------------------------------\n\n    def _try_integer_upscale(self, example_pairs):\n        \"\"\"\n        Detect: output dimensions are k * input dimensions (same k for both\n        height and width, and the same k across all examples). Each input\n        cell at (r, c) becomes a kxk block at rows [k*r, k*r+k) and cols\n        [k*c, k*c+k) in the output, all filled with the same color.\n        \"\"\"\n        if not example_pairs:\n            return None\n\n        factor = None\n        for raw_in, raw_out in example_pairs:\n            ih = len(raw_in)\n            iw = len(raw_in[0]) if raw_in else 0\n            oh = len(raw_out)\n            ow = len(raw_out[0]) if raw_out else 0\n            if ih == 0 or iw == 0 or oh == 0 or ow == 0:\n                return None\n            if oh % ih != 0 or ow % iw != 0:\n                return None\n            kh, kw = oh // ih, ow // iw\n            if kh != kw or kh < 2:\n                return None\n            if factor is None:\n                factor = kh\n            elif factor != kh:\n                return None\n            for r in range(ih):\n                for c in range(iw):\n                    v = raw_in[r][c]\n                    for dr in range(factor):\n                        for dc in range(factor):\n                            if raw_out[r * factor + dr][c * factor + dc] != v:\n                                return None\n\n        if factor is None:\n            return None\n        return {\"type\": \"integer_upscale\", \"factor\": factor, \"confidence\": 1.0}\n\n    # ---- strategy: stack with mirror ------------------------------------\n\n    def _try_stack_with_mirror(self, example_pairs):\n        \"\"\"\n        Detect: output = concatenation of input and a flipped copy of input\n        along one axis. Tries four configurations:\n          - direction=vertical,   order=input_first  (rows: input, vflip(input))\n          - direction=vertical,   order=flip_first   (rows: vflip(input), input)\n          - direction=horizontal, order=input_first  (cols: input, hflip(input))\n          - direction=horizontal, order=flip_first   (cols: hflip(input), input)\n        The same configuration must hold across every example.\n        \"\"\"\n        if not example_pairs:\n            return None\n\n        configs = [\n            (\"vertical\", \"input_first\"),\n            (\"vertical\", \"flip_first\"),\n            (\"horizontal\", \"input_first\"),\n            (\"horizontal\", \"flip_first\"),\n        ]\n\n        for direction, order in configs:\n            ok = True\n            for raw_in, raw_out in example_pairs:\n                if not self._check_stack_mirror(raw_in, raw_out, direction, order):\n                    ok = False\n                    break\n            if ok:\n                return {\n                    \"type\": \"stack_with_mirror\",\n                    \"direction\": direction,\n                    \"order\": order,\n                    \"confidence\": 1.0,\n                }\n        return None\n\n    @staticmethod\n    def _check_stack_mirror(raw_in, raw_out, direction, order):\n        ih = len(raw_in)\n        iw = len(raw_in[0]) if raw_in else 0\n        oh = len(raw_out)\n        ow = len(raw_out[0]) if raw_out else 0\n        if ih == 0 or iw == 0:\n            return False\n\n        if direction == \"vertical\":\n            if ow != iw or oh != 2 * ih:\n                return False\n            flipped = list(reversed(raw_in))\n            top = raw_in if order == \"input_first\" else flipped\n            bot = flipped if order == \"input_first\" else raw_in\n            for r in range(ih):\n                if list(raw_out[r]) != list(top[r]):\n                    return False\n                if list(raw_out[ih + r]) != list(bot[r]):\n                    return False\n            return True\n        else:  # horizontal\n            if oh != ih or ow != 2 * iw:\n                return False\n            flipped = [list(reversed(row)) for row in raw_in]\n            left = raw_in if order == \"input_first\" else flipped\n            right = flipped if order == \"input_first\" else raw_in\n            for r in range(ih):\n                if list(raw_out[r][:iw]) != list(left[r]):\n                    return False\n                if list(raw_out[r][iw:]) != list(right[r]):\n                    return False\n            return True\n\n    # ---- strategy: rectangle interior fill ------------------------------\n\n    def _try_rect_interior_fill(self, example_pairs):\n        \"\"\"\n        Detect: same grid size; input contains hollow rectangular borders of a\n        single foreground color on a background; output equals input except\n        each hollow rect's interior is filled with a color determined by the\n        rect's interior dimensions. Map (interior_h, interior_w) -> fill_color\n        is learned from training and applied to test rectangles.\n        \"\"\"\n        if not example_pairs:\n            return None\n\n        size_to_fill = {}\n        bg_color = None\n        border_color = None\n\n        for raw_in, raw_out in example_pairs:\n            h = len(raw_in)\n            w = len(raw_in[0]) if raw_in else 0\n            if h == 0 or w == 0:\n                return None\n            if h != len(raw_out) or w != (len(raw_out[0]) if raw_out else 0):\n                return None\n\n            # Background = most-frequent color in input\n            counts = {}\n            for row in raw_in:\n                for c in row:\n                    counts[c] = counts.get(c, 0) + 1\n            bg = max(counts, key=counts.get)\n\n            # Foreground colors = everything else; require exactly one\n            fg_set = {c for c in counts if c != bg}\n            if len(fg_set) != 1:\n                return None\n            fg = next(iter(fg_set))\n\n            if bg_color is None:\n                bg_color, border_color = bg, fg\n            elif (bg_color, border_color) != (bg, fg):\n                return None\n\n            rects = self._find_hollow_rects(raw_in, fg, bg)\n            if not rects:\n                return None\n\n            # Build expected output: copy input, fill each rect interior\n            # with the color present in raw_out at the interior cells.\n            for (r0, c0, r1, c1) in rects:\n                ih_int = r1 - r0 - 1\n                iw_int = c1 - c0 - 1\n                if ih_int < 1 or iw_int < 1:\n                    return None\n                fill = raw_out[r0 + 1][c0 + 1]\n                # Interior must be uniform fill color in output\n                for r in range(r0 + 1, r1):\n                    for c in range(c0 + 1, c1):\n                        if raw_out[r][c] != fill:\n                            return None\n                key = (ih_int, iw_int)\n                if key in size_to_fill and size_to_fill[key] != fill:\n                    return None\n                size_to_fill[key] = fill\n\n            # Verify all non-interior cells are unchanged\n            interior_cells = set()\n            for (r0, c0, r1, c1) in rects:\n                for r in range(r0 + 1, r1):\n                    for c in range(c0 + 1, c1):\n                        interior_cells.add((r, c))\n            for r in range(h):\n                for c in range(w):\n                    if (r, c) in interior_cells:\n                        continue\n                    if raw_in[r][c] != raw_out[r][c]:\n                        return None\n\n        if not size_to_fill:\n            return None\n        return {\n            \"type\": \"rect_interior_fill\",\n            \"background\": bg_color,\n            \"border\": border_color,\n            \"size_to_fill\": {f\"{k[0]}x{k[1]}\": v for k, v in size_to_fill.items()},\n            \"confidence\": 1.0,\n        }\n\n    @staticmethod\n    def _find_hollow_rects(raw, fg, bg):\n        \"\"\"Find all hollow rectangles of color fg with interior color bg.\n        Returns list of (r0, c0, r1, c1) bounding boxes.\"\"\"\n        h = len(raw)\n        w = len(raw[0]) if raw else 0\n\n        # Find connected components of fg cells (4-connected)\n        visited = [[False] * w for _ in range(h)]\n        rects = []\n\n        for r in range(h):\n            for c in range(w):\n                if raw[r][c] != fg or visited[r][c]:\n                    continue\n                # BFS\n                comp = []\n                queue = [(r, c)]\n                while queue:\n                    rr, cc = queue.pop(0)\n                    if rr < 0 or rr >= h or cc < 0 or cc >= w:\n                        continue\n                    if visited[rr][cc] or raw[rr][cc] != fg:\n                        continue\n                    visited[rr][cc] = True\n                    comp.append((rr, cc))\n                    for dr, dc in [(-1, 0), (1, 0), (0, -1), (0, 1)]:\n                        queue.append((rr + dr, cc + dc))\n\n                if not comp:\n                    continue\n                rs = [p[0] for p in comp]\n                cs = [p[1] for p in comp]\n                r0, r1 = min(rs), max(rs)\n                c0, c1 = min(cs), max(cs)\n                width = c1 - c0 + 1\n                height = r1 - r0 + 1\n                if width < 3 or height < 3:\n                    continue\n                # Check border is all fg\n                comp_set = set(comp)\n                ok = True\n                for cc in range(c0, c1 + 1):\n                    if (r0, cc) not in comp_set or (r1, cc) not in comp_set:\n                        ok = False\n                        break\n                if ok:\n                    for rr in range(r0, r1 + 1):\n                        if (rr, c0) not in comp_set or (rr, c1) not in comp_set:\n                            ok = False\n                            break\n                if not ok:\n                    continue\n                # Check interior is all bg\n                for rr in range(r0 + 1, r1):\n                    for cc in range(c0 + 1, c1):\n                        if raw[rr][cc] != bg:\n                            ok = False\n                            break\n                    if not ok:\n                        break\n                # Component must be exactly the border (no extra fg cells)\n                expected_border_size = 2 * (height + width) - 4\n                if ok and len(comp) == expected_border_size:\n                    rects.append((r0, c0, r1, c1))\n        return rects\n\n    # ---- strategy: staircase extend right -------------------------------\n\n    def _try_staircase_extend_right(self, example_pairs):\n        \"\"\"\n        Detect: every input is exactly one row of width w; output has\n        oh = w // 2 rows and width w. Row 0 of the output equals the input;\n        each subsequent row extends the colored prefix by one cell to the\n        right (one more cell of the same fg color, rest background).\n        \"\"\"\n        if not example_pairs:\n            return None\n\n        for raw_in, raw_out in example_pairs:\n            if len(raw_in) != 1:\n                return None\n            w = len(raw_in[0])\n            if w < 2:\n                return None\n            oh = len(raw_out)\n            if oh != w // 2 or oh < 1:\n                return None\n            for row in raw_out:\n                if len(row) != w:\n                    return None\n\n            # The prefix color (fg) is the leftmost cell; the rest must be a\n            # single different background color.\n            row0 = list(raw_in[0])\n            distinct = set(row0)\n            if len(distinct) != 2:\n                return None\n            fg = row0[0]\n            bg = next(v for v in distinct if v != fg)\n\n            n = 0\n            while n < w and row0[n] == fg:\n                n += 1\n            if n == 0 or any(v != bg for v in row0[n:]):\n                return None\n\n            # Verify each output row\n            for i in range(oh):\n                expected = [fg] * (n + i) + [bg] * (w - n - i)\n                if list(raw_out[i]) != expected:\n                    return None\n\n        return {\"type\": \"staircase_extend_right\", \"confidence\": 1.0}\n\n\n# ======================================================================\n# DescendOperator -- placeholder for deeper KG exploration\n# ======================================================================\n\nclass DescendOperator(Operator):\n    \"\"\"\n    Placeholder: moves focus to a deeper KG level when current-level\n    analysis is insufficient. Not yet needed for the basic pipeline.\n    \"\"\"\n\n    def __init__(self):\n        super().__init__(\"descend\")\n\n    def precondition(self, wm) -> bool:\n        raise NotImplementedError(\"DescendOperator.precondition() not implemented.\")\n\n    def effect(self, wm):\n        raise NotImplementedError(\"DescendOperator.effect() not implemented.\")\n\n\n# ======================================================================\n# PredictOperator -- apply rule to test input\n# ======================================================================\n\nclass PredictOperator(Operator):\n    \"\"\"\n    Reads the best rule from active-rules and applies it to each test\n    pair's input grid to produce a predicted output grid.\n    \"\"\"\n\n    def __init__(self):\n        super().__init__(\"predict\")\n\n    def precondition(self, wm) -> bool:\n        raise NotImplementedError(\"PredictOperator.precondition() not implemented.\")\n\n    def effect(self, wm):\n        task = wm.task\n        active_rules = wm.s1.get(\"active-rules\")\n        if not task or not active_rules:\n            return\n\n        rule = active_rules[0]\n        predictions = dict(wm.s1.get(\"predictions\") or {})\n\n        for i, test_pair in enumerate(task.test_pairs):\n            key = f\"test_{i}\"\n            if key in predictions:\n                continue\n            g0 = test_pair.input_grid\n            if g0 is None:\n                continue\n            predicted = self._apply_rule(rule, g0)\n            if predicted is not None:\n                predictions[key] = predicted\n\n        wm.s1[\"predictions\"] = predictions\n\n    # ---- rule application dispatchers ------------------------------------\n\n    def _apply_rule(self, rule, input_grid):\n        rule_type = rule.get(\"type\")\n        if rule_type == \"recolor_sequential\":\n            return self._apply_recolor_sequential(rule, input_grid)\n        if rule_type == \"color_mapping\":\n            return self._apply_color_mapping(rule, input_grid)\n        if rule_type == \"bbox_fill\":\n            return self._apply_bbox_fill(rule, input_grid)\n        if rule_type == \"axis_mirror_recolor\":\n            return self._apply_axis_mirror_recolor(rule, input_grid)\n        if rule_type == \"integer_upscale\":\n            return self._apply_integer_upscale(rule, input_grid)\n        if rule_type == \"stack_with_mirror\":\n            return self._apply_stack_with_mirror(rule, input_grid)\n        if rule_type == \"rect_interior_fill\":\n            return self._apply_rect_interior_fill(rule, input_grid)\n        if rule_type == \"staircase_extend_right\":\n            return self._apply_staircase_extend_right(rule, input_grid)\n        if rule_type == \"identity\":\n            return [row[:] for row in input_grid.raw]\n        return None\n\n    def _apply_recolor_sequential(self, rule, input_grid):\n        raw = input_grid.raw\n        height = len(raw)\n        width = len(raw[0]) if raw else 0\n        sort_key = rule[\"sort_key\"]\n        start_color = rule[\"start_color\"]\n        source_colors = set(rule.get(\"source_colors\", []))\n\n        # Find target cells\n        target_cells = []\n        for r in range(height):\n            for c in range(width):\n                if raw[r][c] in source_colors:\n                    target_cells.append((r, c))\n\n        if not target_cells:\n            return [row[:] for row in raw]\n\n        # Group into connected components\n        groups = self._group_positions(target_cells)\n\n        # Sort groups by the rule's sort key\n        def _sort_val(group):\n            if sort_key == \"top_row\":\n                return min(r for r, c in group)\n            if sort_key == \"top_col\":\n                return min(c for r, c in group)\n            return 0\n\n        sorted_groups = sorted(groups, key=_sort_val)\n\n        # Build output grid\n        output = [row[:] for row in raw]\n        for idx, group in enumerate(sorted_groups):\n            new_color = start_color + idx\n            for r, c in group:\n                output[r][c] = new_color\n\n        return output\n\n    def _apply_color_mapping(self, rule, input_grid):\n        raw = input_grid.raw\n        mapping = rule.get(\"mapping\", {})\n\n        output = []\n        for row in raw:\n            output.append([mapping.get(cell, cell) for cell in row])\n        return output\n\n    def _apply_bbox_fill(self, rule, input_grid):\n        raw = input_grid.raw\n        h = len(raw)\n        w = len(raw[0]) if raw else 0\n        marker = rule.get(\"marker\")\n        fg = rule.get(\"foreground\")\n        bg = rule.get(\"background\")\n        if marker is None or fg is None or bg is None:\n            return None\n\n        rows = [r for r in range(h) for c in range(w) if raw[r][c] == fg]\n        cols = [c for r in range(h) for c in range(w) if raw[r][c] == fg]\n        if not rows:\n            return [row[:] for row in raw]\n        r0, r1 = min(rows), max(rows)\n        c0, c1 = min(cols), max(cols)\n\n        out = [row[:] for row in raw]\n        for r in range(r0, r1 + 1):\n            for c in range(c0, c1 + 1):\n                if out[r][c] == bg:\n                    out[r][c] = marker\n        return out\n\n    def _apply_axis_mirror_recolor(self, rule, input_grid):\n        raw = input_grid.raw\n        h = len(raw)\n        w = len(raw[0]) if raw else 0\n        marker = rule.get(\"marker\")\n        fg = rule.get(\"foreground\")\n        axis = rule.get(\"axis\", \"horizontal\")\n        if marker is None or fg is None:\n            return None\n\n        out = [row[:] for row in raw]\n        for r in range(h):\n            for c in range(w):\n                if raw[r][c] != fg:\n                    continue\n                if axis == \"horizontal\":\n                    rr, cc = r, w - 1 - c\n                else:\n                    rr, cc = h - 1 - r, c\n                if (r, c) == (rr, cc):\n                    continue\n                if raw[rr][cc] == fg:\n                    out[r][c] = marker\n        return out\n\n    def _apply_integer_upscale(self, rule, input_grid):\n        raw = input_grid.raw\n        k = rule.get(\"factor\")\n        if not isinstance(k, int) or k < 2:\n            return None\n        out = []\n        for row in raw:\n            new_row = []\n            for v in row:\n                new_row.extend([v] * k)\n            for _ in range(k):\n                out.append(new_row[:])\n        return out\n\n    def _apply_stack_with_mirror(self, rule, input_grid):\n        raw = input_grid.raw\n        direction = rule.get(\"direction\")\n        order = rule.get(\"order\")\n        if direction not in (\"vertical\", \"horizontal\"):\n            return None\n        if order not in (\"input_first\", \"flip_first\"):\n            return None\n\n        if direction == \"vertical\":\n            flipped = list(reversed([row[:] for row in raw]))\n            top = [row[:] for row in raw] if order == \"input_first\" else flipped\n            bot = flipped if order == \"input_first\" else [row[:] for row in raw]\n            return [r[:] for r in top] + [r[:] for r in bot]\n        else:\n            flipped = [list(reversed(row)) for row in raw]\n            left = [row[:] for row in raw] if order == \"input_first\" else flipped\n            right = flipped if order == \"input_first\" else [row[:] for row in raw]\n            return [list(left[r]) + list(right[r]) for r in range(len(raw))]\n\n    def _apply_rect_interior_fill(self, rule, input_grid):\n        raw = input_grid.raw\n        h = len(raw)\n        w = len(raw[0]) if raw else 0\n        bg = rule.get(\"background\")\n        fg = rule.get(\"border\")\n        size_to_fill_raw = rule.get(\"size_to_fill\") or {}\n        if bg is None or fg is None:\n            return None\n        size_to_fill = {}\n        for k, v in size_to_fill_raw.items():\n            try:\n                a, b = k.split(\"x\")\n                size_to_fill[(int(a), int(b))] = v\n            except ValueError:\n                continue\n\n        rects = GeneralizeOperator._find_hollow_rects(raw, fg, bg)\n        out = [row[:] for row in raw]\n        for (r0, c0, r1, c1) in rects:\n            ih = r1 - r0 - 1\n            iw = c1 - c0 - 1\n            fill = size_to_fill.get((ih, iw))\n            if fill is None:\n                continue\n            for r in range(r0 + 1, r1):\n                for c in range(c0 + 1, c1):\n                    out[r][c] = fill\n        return out\n\n    def _apply_staircase_extend_right(self, rule, input_grid):\n        raw = input_grid.raw\n        if len(raw) != 1:\n            return None\n        row0 = list(raw[0])\n        w = len(row0)\n        if w < 2:\n            return None\n        distinct = set(row0)\n        if len(distinct) != 2:\n            return None\n        fg = row0[0]\n        bg = next(v for v in distinct if v != fg)\n        n = 0\n        while n < w and row0[n] == fg:\n            n += 1\n        if n == 0 or any(v != bg for v in row0[n:]):\n            return None\n        oh = w // 2\n        out = []\n        for i in range(oh):\n            cells = [fg] * (n + i) + [bg] * (w - n - i)\n            out.append(cells)\n        return out\n\n    # ---- helpers ---------------------------------------------------------\n\n    @staticmethod\n    def _group_positions(positions):\n        \"\"\"Group (row, col) positions into 4-connected components.\"\"\"\n        pos_set = set(positions)\n        visited = set()\n        groups = []\n\n        for pos in positions:\n            if pos in visited:\n                continue\n            group = []\n            queue = [pos]\n            while queue:\n                p = queue.pop(0)\n                if p in visited or p not in pos_set:\n                    continue\n                visited.add(p)\n                group.append(p)\n                r, c = p\n                for dr, dc in [(-1, 0), (1, 0), (0, -1), (0, 1)]:\n                    nb = (r + dr, c + dc)\n                    if nb in pos_set and nb not in visited:\n                        queue.append(nb)\n            groups.append(group)\n\n        return groups\n\n\n# ======================================================================\n# SubmitOperator -- finalize and satisfy goal\n# ======================================================================\n\nclass SubmitOperator(Operator):\n    \"\"\"\n    Writes predicted grids to S1 output-link in the format expected by\n    run_task.py, and marks the goal as satisfied.\n    \"\"\"\n\n    def __init__(self):\n        super().__init__(\"submit\")\n\n    def precondition(self, wm) -> bool:\n        raise NotImplementedError(\"SubmitOperator.precondition() not implemented.\")\n\n    def effect(self, wm):\n        predictions = wm.s1.get(\"predictions\")\n        if not predictions:\n            return\n\n        task = wm.task\n        if not task:\n            return\n\n        predicted_grids = []\n        for i in range(len(task.test_pairs)):\n            grid = predictions.get(f\"test_{i}\")\n            if grid is not None:\n                predicted_grids.append(grid)\n\n        if not predicted_grids:\n            return\n\n        # Write to output-link (format expected by run_task.py)\n        wm.s1[\"S1\"] = {\"output-link\": \"O_out\"}\n        wm.s1[\"O_out\"] = {\"predicted-grid\": predicted_grids}\n\n        # Mark goal as satisfied\n        wm.s1[\"goal\"] = {\"subgoals\": {\n            f\"test_{i}\": {\"status\": \"solved\"}\n            for i in range(len(predicted_grids))\n        }}\n\n\nclass VerifyOperator(SubmitOperator):\n    \"\"\"Alias for the verify operation (same mechanism as submit).\"\"\"\n\n    def __init__(self):\n        super().__init__()\n        self.name = \"verify\"\n","numLines":1289,"startLine":1,"totalLines":1289}}}
